{{Nihongo|"'''Ashita, Haru ga Kitara'''"|明日、春が来たら||"Tomorrow, If Spring Comes"}} is a song by Japanese entertainer [[Takako Matsu]] from her debut album, ''[[Sora no Kagami]]'' (1997). It was released on March 21, 1997, through [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG Japan]] as her debut [[single (music)|single]]. The song was written by Yūji Sakamoto and Daisuke Hinata, while Hinata produced the song. Following the wrap-up of the drama ''[[Long Vacation]]'', she decided to give singing a try upon the suggestion of one of its directors.

The track was recorded in [[Santa Monica, California]], and is a mid-tempo [[J-pop]] song composed in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[B minor]]. Its lyrics recite a young girl's memories of her love for a boy in her high school days. It has been praised by critics and associated with the onset of spring in Japan, having re-entered the airplay charts in Japan around that time, even years after its initial release. It has also been covered by many other artists like [[Namie Amuro]], [[Masaharu Fukuyama]], [[Ayumi Shibata]], and [[ClariS]]. The single peaked at number 8 on the [[Oricon]] singles chart and spent 20 weeks in the top 20 of the chart. It was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] (RIAJ) for shipments exceeding 400,000 copies.<ref name="RIAJ-jul1997"/>

Ten years after its initial release, Matsu released a new version of the song titled "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara 97–07" in March 2007. The re-release contains updated lyrics reflecting changes in the artist's mind. By intermixing her vocals with her vocals from 10 years before, new version contrasts the two. The new version was featured on her album ''Cherish You'' (2007) and also on her compilation album ''Footsteps: 10th Anniversary Complete Best'' (2008). As of 2014, Matsu has performed the song on all of her concert tours as well as other events, including [[NHK]]'s ''[[Kōhaku Uta Gassen]]'' in 1997.

==Background and release==
Growing up, Takako Matsu practiced piano and took vocal training as a child.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv-asahi.co.jp/announcer/personal/men/matsui/essay/06.html|script-title=ja:役得?松たか子さんと対談!?|trans-title=Perks? Interview with Matsu Takako!?|publisher=[[TV Asahi]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name="nhk"/> Prior to releasing music, she acted in various television drama and plays.<ref name="pia">{{cite web|url=http://www.pia.co.jp/interview/matsutakako/index.html|script-title=ja:松たか子 ／ インタビュー ／＠ぴあ|trans-title=Takako Matsu Interview @PIA |publisher=PIA Japan|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 3, 2014}}</ref><ref name="asahi">{{cite web|url=http://publications.asahi.com/jn/intreview/091.shtml|script-title=ja:松 たか子 インタビュー: ひたすらに ひたむきに|trans-title=Takako Matsu interview: intently, earnestly |work=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|publisher=Tadakazu Kimura|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref> In 1996, she acted in the drama ''[[Long Vacation]]'', which became very popular in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zakzak.co.jp/geino/n_October/nws146.html|script-title=ja:「ロンバケ」が帰ってくる|trans-title='Ronbake' is coming back|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970209154038/http://www.zakzak.co.jp/geino/n_October/nws146.html|archivedate=February 9, 1997|date=October 1996|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/otona/hobby/artiste/20140527-OYT8T50146.html |script-title=ja:松たか子 「アナ雪」で再ブレイクのヒミツ |trans-title=Takako Matsu: the secret of her ''Frozen'' second big break |work=[[The Yomiuri Shimbun]] |publisher=Yomiuri Group |date=May 30, 2014 |language=Japanese |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140603000633/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/otona/hobby/artiste/20140527-OYT8T50146.html |archivedate=June 3, 2014 |accessdate=May 31, 2014 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> At the wrap up party of the drama, the director of the series at that time heard her perform karaoke and suggested that she try singing.{{ref label|note_a1|note}}<ref name="nhk"/> Although taken aback and hesitant at first, she later agreed, as she felt it was not a chance that everyone received and because she liked singing; she felt it might work out somehow.<ref name="nhk"/>

"Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" was written by Yūji Sakamoto and Daisuke Hinata, both of whom had worked with Matsu. Sakamoto had been ''[[Tokyo Love Story]]''{{'}}s screenwriter and Hinata had been in charge of the music of ''Long Vacation''.<ref name="zakzak1"/> Hinata provided the music and [[arrangement]] to "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara".<ref name="linern"/> The track was recorded at the Hyper Image Studio in [[Santa Monica, California]],<ref name="nhk">{{cite episode|title=NHK プレミアム10 松たか子～彼女が歌う理由～|trans-title=NHK Premium 10. Takako Matsu: The reason why she sings|station=[[NHK]] Japan|date=November 9, 2007|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref name="alblin"/> in January 1997.<ref name="zakzak1">{{cite web|url=http://www.zakzak.co.jp/geino/n_January/nws421.html|script-title=ja:松たか子が歌手デビュー|trans-title=Takako Matsu makes her musical debut|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970714084242/http://www.zakzak.co.jp/geino/n_January/nws421.html|archivedate=July 14, 1997|date=January 9, 1997|publisher=ZakZak. Sankei Digital|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name="zakzak2">{{cite web|url=http://www.zakzak.co.jp/geino/n_January/nws421.html|script-title=ja:松たか子帰国|trans-title=Matsu returns to Japan|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970714084242/http://www.zakzak.co.jp/geino/n_January/nws421.html|archivedate=July 14, 1997|date=January 16, 1997|language=Japanese|publisher=ZakZak. Sankei Digital|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref> Hinata himself mixed the audio while Steve Hall [[audio mastering|mastered]] it.<ref name="alblin">{{cite AV media notes|year=1997|title=[[Sora no Kagami]]|type=liner notes|others=[[Takako Matsu]]|publisher=BMG Japan|id=BVCR-791}}</ref> [[Cagnet (band)|Cagnet]] provided instrumentation to the song.<ref name="alblin"/> The record was [[record producer|produced]] by [[Kozo Nagayama]], who had also produced ''Long Vacation''. Initially, another song was selected to be released as Matsu's debut single.<ref name="pia"/> However, it was scrapped for unknown reasons and "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" was selected instead.<ref name="pia"/> Matsu debuted the song on radio on February 14, 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kyosyuku.net/10news/070203.html|title=松たか子　デビュー曲がNTTのCM曲にも|trans-title=Takako Matsu's debut song is also the CM song for NTT|last=Nashimoto|first=Masaru|authorlink=Masaru Nashimoto|date=February 10, 1997|language=Japanese|publisher=kyosyuku.net|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref> and the single was physically released on March 21, 1997 through BMG Japan as an [[Mini CD single|8&nbsp;cm CD single]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookoffonline.co.jp/old/0001103226|title=【８ｃｍ】明日、春が来たら： 中古CD： 松たか子：ブックオフオンライン|trans-title=[8cm] Ashita, Haru ga Kitara: Second hand CDs: Takako Matsu: Book Off Online|publisher=Bookoffonline|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref>

==Composition==
{{listen
 | filename     = Takako Matsu - Ashita, Haru ga Kitara.ogg
 | title        = "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" (1997)
 | description  = A 26-second sample of the song illustrating its production and the lyrics which see a girl recollect the memories with her high school lover, and uses references to baseball such as "winning ball", the "cheers from the stadium", and "spike footprints" (referring to baseball [[Cleat (shoe)|cleat]]s).<ref name="lyric"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.goo.ne.jp/lyric/LYRUTND9661/index.html|script-title=ja:明日、春が来たら|trans-title=Ashita, Haru ga Kitara|publisher=[[Goo (search engine)|Goo]]. [[NTT Resonant Inc.|NTT Resonant]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 1, 2014|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602202711/http://music.goo.ne.jp/lyric/LYRUTND9661/index.html|archive-date=June 2, 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref>
| pos = left
| format       = [[Ogg]]
}}

"Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" is a mid-tempo [[J-pop]] track with a "gentle melody",<ref name="cdj">{{cite web|url=http://artist.cdjournal.com/d/five-years---singles/3201100769|title=松たか子 / Five Years ~ Singles|work=CDJournal|publisher=Ongaku Shuppansha|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> that lasts for 4 minutes and 13 seconds.<ref name="rs">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/goods/detail/302605|title=松たか子 「明日、春が来たら」 {{!}} BVDR-1151 |trans-title=Takako Matsu "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara"|work=Billboard Japan|publisher=[[Hankyu Hanshin Holdings]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> According to the original [[sheet music|score]] published by Doremi Music Publishing, it is composed in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[B minor]] and in the common [[verse-chorus]] song structure with a [[tempo]] of 110 beats per minute.<ref name="sheet">{{cite web|url=http://www.at-elise.com/elise/JPDPDO00334/|script-title=ja:明日、春が来たら／楽譜：メロディ譜／松 たか子|trans-title=Ashita, Haru ga Kitara/sheet music, melody line/Takako Matsu|publisher=At-Elise / Doremi Music Publishing|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> The track opens with an [[instrumental]] [[introduction (music)|introduction]] with a chord progression of Gmaj<sub>7</sub>–F{{music|sharp}}m<sub>7</sub>–Bm.<ref name="sheet"/> As it reaches the chorus, the progression shifts to G–A–F{{music|sharp}}m–Bm<sub>7</sub>.<ref name="sheet"/> The same pattern is repeated throughout the song.<ref name="sheet"/>

The lyrics of the song, written from the perspective of a girl, sees her recollect the memories of her love with a member of her [[High school baseball in Japan|high school baseball]] team and how she hopes to meet him again "tomorrow, if spring comes".<ref name="alblin"/><ref name="lyric">{{cite web|url=http://www.navida.ne.jp/sangyo/music/bn.html|script-title=ja:私の一曲　バックナンバー |trans-title=My Songs: archive|publisher=Navida|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> Upon the album's release, Yoshitake Maeda, writing for BMG Japan, commented that Sakamoto probably reminisced on his teenage years through the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmgjapan.com/mats/album.htm|title= BMG Japan: Takako Matsu|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19981205005138/http://www.bmgjapan.com/mats/album.htm|archivedate=December 5, 1998|language=Japanese|publisher=BMG Japan|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref>

The [[b-side]] of the single "Zutto... Iyō yo" was written by Matsu and produced by Hinata.<ref name="linern"/> Matsu decided to give it the theme of three girls going out for a drive.<ref name="kado">{{cite journal|title=総力特集 松たか子 これが私の生きる舞台（ステージ）|trans-title=Takako Matsu Massive Feature Article: This is the stage on which I live|date=August 1997|work=Monthly Kadokawa|publisher=[[Kadokawa Corporation]]|place=Japan|pages=20–67|volume=15|issue=8|id=KAD15-8}}</ref> However, she commented that no matter how others looked at it, it seemed as if the song is about two girls.<ref name="kado"/> The song opens with an "[[electronic music|electro]]" introduction and utilizes a warped guitar throughout.<ref name="cdj2">{{cite web|url=http://artist.cdjournal.com/d/-/1197070746|script-title=ja:松たか子 / 空の鏡|trans-title=Takako Matsu / Sora no Kagami|work=CDJournal|publisher=Ongaku Shuppansha|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> In addition to the two songs, the single also featured the original [[karaoke]] track to "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara".<ref name="linern">{{cite AV media notes|title=Ashita, Haru ga Kitara|type=CD single back cover|others=[[Takako Matsu]]|publisher=BMG Japan|id=BVDR-1151}}</ref> An [[LP record|LP]] titled ''Remix Hyper Bug'' containing remixes of "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" by DJ Craig William—"Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" (Hyper Bug Mix) and "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" (Techno Dub Mix) was released on August 21, 1997 through [[BMG Victor]]. It also features a remix of the album track "Love Sick", titled "Love Sick (Deep Sick Mix)".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tower.co.jp/item/2291840/Hyper-Bug-Mix|title=松たか子 / Hyper Bug Mix|publisher=[[Tower Records]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531142656/http://www.tower.co.jp/item/2291840/Hyper-Bug-Mix|archive-date=May 31, 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref>

==Reception==
[[File:Sakurazaka_03.jpg|thumb|right|"Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" has often been associated with [[spring (season)|spring]] in Japan]]
A reviewer for ''CD Journal'' commended "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" for being "pure" and noted that Matsu's "unobtrusive [and] naked voice" is like "sitting in a sunny spot on early spring day".<ref name="cdj"/> Similarly, ''Rolling Stone Japan'' wrote that the song has a "heartwarming" production, which they noted has become synonymous with Takako Matsu.<ref name="rs"/> Another reviewer for ''CD Journal'' said that the b-side, "Zutto... Iyō yo"{{'}}s arrangement makes it an "impressive pop song".<ref name="cdj2"/> Since its release, "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" has often been associated with the onset of spring in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.excite.co.jp/News/car/20140329/Clicccar_250451.html|script-title=ja:お花見やキャンプで大活躍！今、人気の広々軽自動車5台！(1/2)|trans-title=Everyone's doing hanami and going camping! The 5 most popular spacious kei cars at the moment.|language=Japanese|date=May 29, 2014|publisher=[[Excite]] Japan|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhk.or.jp/osaka/namihana/2013nendo/diary1403.html|title=FMサウンドポケット なみはな|trans-title=FM sound pocket: Namihana|publisher=[[NHK]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531104805/http://www.nhk.or.jp/osaka/namihana/2013nendo/diary1403.html|archive-date=May 31, 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://joysound.com/ex/st/special/feature/moriagaru/harusong_02/index.htm|script-title=ja:注目特集！カラオケで盛り上がる曲～春うた編～|trans-title=Special: Songs that win over at karaoke: spring song edition |publisher=JoySound. Xing Inc|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmk.fm/program/special/111223max.php|script-title=ja:リクエスト一覧曲|trans-title=Request list|language=Japanese|publisher=FM Kumamoto. FMK Satellite Studio|accessdate=June 2, 2014|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714222449/http://www.fmk.fm/program/special/111223max.php|archive-date=July 14, 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref> The song also entered the top requests list of many [[FM radio]] stations around the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.at-s.com/sbsradio/program/denriku/|title=鳳楽・上ちゃんの歌謡曲 電リクでナイト {{!}} SBS RADIO|trans-title=Hōraku, Uechan's kayōkyoku. Denriku night |publisher=SBS Radio. [[Shizuoka Shimbun|Shizuoka Broadcasting System]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref> Since the introduction of ''Billboard'' Japan in 2010, the song has spiked on its airplay charts during the time of spring.<ref>''Billboard'' Japan peak positions:
*{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=adult_airplay&year=2010&month=03&day=08|title=''Billboard'' Japan Adult Contemporary Airplay: March 8, 2010|work=Billboard Japan|publisher=Hankyu Hanshin Holdings|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=top_airplay&year=2011&month=03&day=14|title=''Billboard'' Japan Hot 100 Airplay: March 14, 2011|work=Billboard Japan|publisher=Hankyu Hanshin Holdings|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail/?a=adult_airplay&year=2012&month=03&day=12|title=''Billboard'' Japan Adult Contemporary Airplay: March 12, 2012|work=Billboard Japan|publisher=Hankyu Hanshin Holdings|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=top_airplay&year=2013&month=03&day=11|title=''Billboard'' Japan Hot 100 Airplay: March 11, 2013|work=Billboard Japan|publisher=Hankyu Hanshin Holdings|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=top_airplay&year=2014&month=03&day=24|title=''Billboard'' Japan Hot 100 Airplay: March 24, 2014|work=Billboard Japan|publisher=Hankyu Hanshin Holdings|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=adult_airplay&year=2015&month=03&day=9|title=''Billboard'' Japan Adult Contemporary Airplay: March 9, 2015|work=Billboard Japan|publisher=Hankyu Hanshin Holdings|language=Japanese|accessdate=March 5, 2015}}</ref> It was also included on the compilation ''True Love: Spring Memorial Songs'' in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/music/release/d/501992/1/|title=TRUE　LOVE～SPRING　MEMORIAL　SONGS～／オムニバス|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref> In a web poll conducted in 2013 by ''MyNavi'' news asking people about their favorite spring song, "Ashita, Haru ga Kitara" was ranked at number 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lifestyle.jp.msn.com/life/love/mynavi/あなたが好きな「春をテーマにした曲」は何ですか？|title=あなたが好きな「春をテーマにした曲」は何ですか？|trans-title=What are your favorite "spring-themed" songs?|publisher=[[MSN]] Japan Lifestyle / MyNavi|date=March 1, 2013|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref>

The single debuted at number 15 on the [[Oricon]] singles chart during the week following its release in March 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?kbn=js&types=rnk&sw=+&search_type=single&year=1997&month=3&week=5&web.x=27&web.y=2|title=検索結果-ORICON STYLE|trans-title=Search results: Oricon Style|publisher=[[Oricon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> selling 35,640 copies. A few weeks later, it moved to number 8, moving 46,400&nbsp;copies, which became its peak position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?kbn=js&types=rnk&sw=+&search_type=single&year=1997&month=4&week=4&web.x=27&web.y=2|title=検索結果-ORICON STYLE|trans-title=Search results: Oricon Style|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref><ref name="oricsingle">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/219459/products/music/59001/1/|script-title=ja:「明日，春が来たら」 松たか子|trans-title="Ashita Haru ga Kitara" Takako Matsu|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 3, 2014}}</ref> The single spent nine weeks in the top 20, including two in the top 10, and finished at number 75 on the yearly chart, due to sales of 428,170&nbsp;copies. As of May 2014, it has sold 431,540&nbsp;copies in Japan and has been certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] for shipments of over 400,000&nbsp;copies.{{ref label|note_a2|note}}<ref name="RIAJ-jul1997">{{cite journal |title=GOLD ALBUM 他認定作品 1997年5月度 |trans-title=Gold Albums, and other certified works. May 1997 Edition |url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/issue/record/1997/199707.pdf |format=PDF | journal=The Record |type=Bulletin |language=Japanese |location=[[Chūō, Tokyo]] |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] |publication-date=July 10, 1997 |volume=453 |page=9 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223094347/http://www.riaj.or.jp/issue/record/1997/199707.pdf |archivedate=February 23, 2014 |accessdate=May 3, 2014}}</ref><ref name="OriconSales">{{cite web | title=オリコンランキング情報サービス「you大樹」 |trans-title=Oricon Ranking Information Service 'You Big Tree' | url=http://ranking.oricon.co.jp | work=Oricon |url-access=subscription | accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref>

==Live performances and covers==
In 1997, Matsu performed the song at the 48th [[Kōhaku Uta Gassen]] in 1997, representing the "Red" team in the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.nhk.or.jp/kouhaku/history/history_48.html|title=NHK紅白歌合戦ヒストリー|trans-title=NHK ''Kōhaku Uta Gassen'' history |publisher=[[NHK]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 3, 2014}}</ref> The previous year, before her debut as a singer, she had hosted the "Red" team. This made Matsu, who was 19 at that time, the youngest person to reach that position in the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.nhk.or.jp/kouhaku/history/list.html|title=NHK紅白歌合戦ヒストリー|trans-title=NHK ''Kōhaku Uta Gassen'' history|publisher=NHK|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/219459/profile/history/p/1/r/|title=松たか子のプロフィール・ヒストリー {{!}} オリコン芸能人事典|trans-title=Takako Matsu's profile history: Oricon entertainer database|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> In June of the same year, she appeared on the show ''Love Love Aishiteru'', her first music talk show appearance, and performed the song along with a cover of [[Seiko Matsuda]]'s "Hitomi wa Diamond" (1983).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.zakzak.co.jp/geino/n_June97/nws886.html|script-title=ja:松たか子が歌番組に初出演|trans-title=Matsu Takako's first appearance on a music show|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19981206185800/http://www2.zakzak.co.jp/geino/n_June97/nws886.html|archivedate=December 6, 1998|publisher=ZakZak. [[Sankei Shimbun|Sankei Digital]]|date=June 2, 1997|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref> She has performed the song on all of her concert tours—from the Piece of Life (2001) through Time for Music (2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artist.cdjournal.com/d/-/2201120443|title=松たか子 / concert tour vol.1 "a piece of life" on film <nowiki>[VIDEO]</nowiki>|work=CDJournal|publisher=Ongaku Shuppansha|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://artist.cdjournal.com/d/concert-tour-2003-second-wave/3204012042|title=松たか子 / concert tour 2003 "second wave"|work=CDJournal|publisher=Ongaku Shuppansha|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref><ref name="conc07">{{cite web|url=http://artist.cdjournal.com/d/matsu-takako-concert-tour-2007-i-cherish-you-on-f/4207091266|title=松たか子 / MATSU TAKAKO concert tour 2007 "I Cherish You" on film <nowiki>[DVD]</nowiki>|work=CDJournal|publisher=Ongaku Shuppansha|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref><ref name="conc10">{{cite web|url=http://artist.cdjournal.com/d/takako-matsu-concert-tour-2010time-for-music/4210070897|title=松たか子 / Takako Matsu Concert Tour 2010 "Time for Music" <nowiki>[DVD]</nowiki>|work=CDJournal|publisher=Ongaku Shuppansha|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> On the Cherish You (2007) and Time for Music concert tours, she performed the 97–07 version of the song.<ref name="conc07"/><ref name="conc10"/> A footage of performance from the Piece of Life tour was used to promote the DVD release of the concert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itmedia.co.jp/lifestyle/articles/0403/23/news066.html|script-title=ja:松たか子「明日、春が来たら」1週間限定でライブ映像を無料公開|trans-title=Takako Matsu's 'Tomorrow, If Spring Comes', available for streaming for a week|date=March 23, 2004|publisher=ITmedia. ITmedia Inc|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 7, 2014}}</ref>

Apart from the tours, she has also performed the song on various televised appearances. In 2003, she appeared on the talk show hosted by Japanese singer [[Ayumi Hamasaki]] and performed the song and "Ashita ni Kuchizuke o" (2003) alongside Hamasaki.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fujitv.co.jp/AYU/guest020-1.html|title=ayu ready?：ゲスト|date=February 2003|publisher=[[Fuji TV]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> Three years later, Matsu sang the song on ''[[Music Fair]]'', alongside [[Sukima Switch]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fujitv.co.jp/MUSICFAIR/setlist141101.html |title=MUSIC FAIR {{!}} SETLIST |publisher=[[Fuji TV]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114053124/http://www.fujitv.co.jp/MUSICFAIR/setlist141101.html |archivedate=January 14, 2015 |language=Japanese |accessdate=May 16, 2015 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> In 2009, Matsu performed the song on the [[FM802]] sponsored event Radio Magic, with Yoshiyuki Sahashi directing the backing band to a crowd of about 12,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nikkansports.com/entertainment/news/f-et-tp0-20090601-501491.html|title=松たか子がFMイベントで夫婦共演|trans-title=Takako Matsu appears with her husband at a radio event|work=[[Nikkan Sports]]|date=June 1, 2009|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref> A writer for Barks wrote that Matsu's vocals sounded "transparent" and the whole performance had a "refreshing feeling".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000049853|title=FM802主催<nowiki><RADIO MAGIC></nowiki>、歴史に残る感動と興奮の2日間 {{!}} FM802|trans-title=FM802's Radio Magic, two days of emotions and excitement for the history books|publisher=Barks. Global Plus, Inc|date=June 2, 2009|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> Oricon magazine commented that Matsu sang "cheerfully" while "running around the stage".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/photogallery/livereport/429/|title=RADIO MAGIC 『"みんなが聴きたい曲"だらけのスペシャルライブ!』|trans-title=Radio Magic: a special live with all the songs everyone wants to hear!|publisher=Oricon|date=June 5, 2009|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> The same year, she performed it on the {{nihongo|''Christmas no Yakusoku 2009''|クリスマスの約束2009|}} show organized by TBS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tbs.co.jp/tbs-ch/item/o1241/|script-title=ja:小田和正「クリスマスの約束2009」|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Tokyo Broadcasting System|TBS]]|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, she performed the song again for [[NHK]], at the {{nihongo|''J-Pop Heisei Music Graffiti''|J-POP 平成ミュージック・グラフィティー|}} event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhk.or.jp/r1-night/heisei/music/201403.html|script-title=ja:2014年3月の曲目リスト |trans-title=March 2014 song order list|publisher=[[NHK]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 5, 2014}}</ref>

The song was covered by [[Hiromi Hirata]] as [[List of The Idolmaster characters|Makoto Kikuchi]] of ''[[The Idolmaster]]'' series as a "Special Request" song. It was later included in the album, ''The Idolmaster Special Spring'' (2010), released through [[Nippon Columbia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://columbia.jp/idolmaster/2009/news/100212.html|title=「THE IDOLM@STER」シリーズ最新情報(2月12日付)～「MASTER SPECIAL SPRING」ジャケット完成!～|trans-title=The Idolmaster series new information (February 12): Master Special Spring CD artwork unveiled!|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507130821/http://columbia.jp/idolmaster/2009/news/100212.html|archivedate=May 7, 2014|publisher=[[Nippon Columbia]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://columbia.jp/idolmaster/2009/COCX-36107.html |title=THE IDOLM@STER MASTER SPECIAL SPRING |language=Japanese |publisher=Nippon Columbia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403141954/http://columbia.jp/idolmaster/2009/COCX-36107.html |archivedate=April 3, 2016 |date=February 2016 |accessdate=May 7, 2014 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> The album peaked at number 18 on the Oricon Albums Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/music/release/d/857944/1/|title=THE IDOLM@STER MASTER SPECIAL SPRING / ゲーム・ミュージック|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 31, 2014}}</ref> It was also covered for the spring compilation ''Cafe de Nagareru Sweet Jazz 20 the Best Sakura Songs'', which peaked at number 39 on the Oricon albums chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/572236/products/music/1062836/1/|title=カフェで流れるSWEET　JAZZ　20　THE　BEST　SAKURA　SONGS|publisher=Oricon|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref> The song has also been covered by many mainstream [[pop music|pop]] artists like [[Namie Amuro]] in 1997, for the show {{nihongo|''The Yoru mo Hippare''|THE夜もヒッパレ||"The Night of Hit Parade"}},<ref>{{Cite episode | series=THE夜もヒッパレ | network= [[Nippon TV]] | location= Tokyo | date= April 19, 1997 | language= Japanese}}</ref> in 1998 by [[Masaharu Fukuyama]] for ''[[All Night Nippon]]'',<ref>{{Cite episode | series=福山雅治のオールナイトニッポン 魂のラジオ | network= [[Nippon Broadcasting System]] | location= Tokyo | date= March 3, 1998 | language= Japanese}}</ref> and in 2008 by [[Ayumi Shibata]] for {{nihongo|''Uta Doki! Pop Classics''|歌ドキッ! 〜ポップクラシックス〜}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artist.cdjournal.com/d/-/4208031130|title=歌ドキッ!～POP CLASSICS～Vol.11 <nowiki>[DVD]</nowiki>|work=CDJournal|publisher=Ongaku Shuppansha|language=Japanese|accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref>

